{
  "text": "Normal murine ASL composition. The values for the ions detected in murine ASL and plasma are shown in Table 1 . Although results in plasma were as expected, the major ionic species Na \u03e9 and Cl \u03ea were significantly lower in ASL than they were in plasma. This finding is consistent with previous reports of low ASL salinity in other species, including measurements from the rat collected in vivo (10) and the horse collected in vitro [CITATION_1] . Perhaps more importantly, ASL collected from human subjects has been reported repeatedly to have lower Na \u03e9 and Cl \u03ea levels than those in plasma [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In all of these reports (except Ref. 14, which reports only Cl \u03ea values), the Na \u03e9 from normal ASL was reported to be between 80 and 85 mM. Therefore, our finding of 87.2 \u03ee 3.0 mM Na \u03e9 is in agreement with previous reports. We did, however, find a considerably lower Cl \u03ea value than has been reported by others (57.0 \u03ee 3.0 mM vs. a range of 84-108 mM) [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , with the presence of a considerable anion gap (30 mM). Additionally, we found considerably lower values for K \u03e9 in ASL than previously reported (4.7 \u03ee 0.4 vs. 20-29 mM), with approximately equivalent values between ASL and plasma. Given that osmolarity is often determined from two times Na \u03e9 and K \u03e9 concentration, the apparent osmolarity of this liquid was 183 mosM compared with \u03f3250 mosM for plasma. However, it is important to note that we were not able to directly measure osmolarity. We additionally report values for HCO [CITATION_10] \u03ea and PO 4 3\u03ea to be lower in mouse ASL than in plasma, while SO 4 2\u03ea levels are higher. Ionic composition of ASL from B6-Cftr UNC\u03ea/\u03ea and B6-Cftr UNC\u03e9/\u03e9 mice. ASL from CF patients has been reported to exhibit either elevated salinity [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] or identical levels of Na \u03e9 or Cl \u03ea compared with normal subjects [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] . To evaluate the contribution of functional CFTR Cl \u03ea channels to ASL composition, we attempted to collect ASL from a knockout mouse strain raised on a C57BL/6 background in which the gene encoding the CFTR protein has been disrupted. Although we successfully sampled ASL from four of eight B6-Cftr UNC\u03ea/\u03ea mice (a similar success rate to normal C57BL/6 mice), we were only able to collect a sufficient quantity of ASL for reproducible CE analysis from two of these mice. Results were similar between B6-Cftr UNC\u03ea/\u03ea mice (Na \u03e9 , 84.8 \u03ee 5.7 mM; K \u03e9 , 4.8 \u03ee 0.01 mM; Cl \u03ea , 49.1 \u03ee 18.9 mM; HCO 3 \u03ea , 4.8 \u03ee 1.6 mM) and their littermate B6-Cftr UNC\u03e9/\u03e9 controls (Na \u03e9 , 85.6 \u03ee 15.8 mM; K \u03e9 , 5.2 \u03ee 1.1 mM; Cl \u03ea , 66.2 \u03ee 7.8 mM; HCO 3 \u03ea , 5.1 \u03ee 0.7 mM).",
